description.text:
Want to drain something through cheesecloth? This stand holds both standard and wide-mouthed mason jars - 2 3/4" (70mm) and 3 3/8" (86mm). I put it in a tupperware sandwich container, which allows for about 2/3 cup (160 ml) of water to drain out before reaching the lid of a standard-mouthed jar, and over 1 1/4 cups (300 ml) of water to drain from a wide-mouthed jar.

I am using mine for sprouting seeds. I could also see it used in cheesemaking, when draining the whey from the curds. In either case, be aware that 3d printed parts are difficult to impossible to sanitize, with all of the seams, cracks, and voids, so there is a risk of illness if used for food or drink.

description.text:
Easter Egg Maker 2016 - "Egg-O-Matic"

"It Slices!!! It Dices!!! It makes fancy colored Easter Eggs!!! Try THAT with a brush and roller.

Here's Easter Egg Maker 2016, "Egg-O-Matic" for customizer and OpenSCAD. The great thing is you can make MULTI-COLORED eggs on any printer. For example, to make 2 color eggs, you would print the SAME stl file 2 times, once in each color. Swap the pieces around and you'll have enough to make 2 eggs in 2 colors. You can swap the pieces around a lot of different ways depending on the number of cuts.

How to Use Egg-O-Matic in Customizer

Step 1 - Adjust the size and shape - the default settings are for a standard 60mm hen's egg. If you are making Easter eggs you can go to Step 2. If you wish to make other sized eggs or other shapes, check out the 'Size and Shape' tab. You can adjust the the settings to get anything ranging from a perfect sphere to a blimp, in the exact size you need.

Step 2 - Choose how many pieces. First you'll need to decide how many cuts you want to make on the long axis of the egg. The more cuts take slightly longer to print and are more complicated to work with. For children, stick to lower numbers. For more cuts, you might consider making the egg a little bit larger.

Step 3 - Choose a cutter. You have a choice of three different style cutters: flat, linear, and radial. The flat cutter is best for making stripped or checked patterns. The linear cutter moves in a straight line and produces more unusual patterns on the egg surface that will not be the same all the way around the egg. The radial cutter produces the same pattern all the way around the surface.

Step 4 - Choose a wave pattern for making the cuts. Pick from sine, abs(sine), tri, saw, or square wave. You'll also need to choose how many cycles for the cutter to make and the amplitude of the cut. SECRET: to make flat diagonal cuts, use the sine cutter with cycles set to 1 and use AMP to control the angle of the cut.

Step 5 - Choose how many cuts to make around the egg. This will determine how many color changes you can have going around the egg. This is normally 2 for a bisected egg, but you can crank it up for a checkered egg and other effects. Keep in mind this multiplies the number of pieces you will end up with and makes each piece that much smaller.

Please post your makes so we can start a nice library of designs.

Please let me know if you have any problems or requests.

For those interested in learning about how this works, I'll be putting a code walk-through up on my blog at ricswika.com over the next few days.

HAPPY EASTER 2016!!!!.

title: Rotating Skull Gear with snap pins

description.text:
I've learned that I have a thing for 3D printing geared objects and decided to print CarryTheWhat's Rotating Skull Gears. This is a great mashup between Emmett's gear code and a Skull image by bothacker.

This was actually one of my first prints a couple years back, but my machine was not tuned well and it did not turn well. After having great success with Emmett's new parametric snap pins, I thought that this might benefit from a conversion to the new pin type, so I loaded the files into Tinkercad, plugged the holes and created the new ones that work with the parametric snap pins.

I made one minor mistake when doing the conversion. I used the standard pin size which was just slightly too long for the center piece. I did some testing and found that all I had to do was to cut off the tip of the pins that go into those holes. Long story short, it goes together well and works great! Just add a little of your favorite lubricant. I recommend either silicone spray or white lithium grease.

And again hats off to CarryTheWhat for the great design!

Rafts:

No

Resolution:

.2mm

Infill:

10%

Notes:

Print one of each gear piece, one center piece and 8 pins. I recommend printing an extra pin or two just in case.

The pieces can print with no support, which is what I did. If you do this, you will get some stringing when it prints the jaw bone below the ear, but it should clean up alright. Or you could use support. The rest do not need support.

First clean up any stringing and make sure that the gears look clean. I also like to take an exacto knife and clean of the edge of the rotating hole on each gear where the plastick sticks out slightly from squishing the first print layer.

On to assembly-
First, I put the pins into the skull gears pointed end first. Make sure that the end of the pin that sticks out is the cut off end. lubricated them turning them a few turns to work in the lube. I used white lithium grease spray.

Then assemble the skull by connecting the pieces to the center piece. I recommend looking at the original skull model to determine orientation. You can find it here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3400

First I connect all four of the large pieces to the center. They go on the large sides of the center piece taking care to put them on the right sides in relation to each other. They will be able to spin freely so that you can line them up as you add each small gear. I then added the nose bridge and the bottom pieces because they are easy to line up. The other two corners are different sizes, so it is easy to tell which goes where.

Ever since I saw the Mobius Heart earlier this week:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13861 I've been slaving away at the forge trying to replicate that feat in a solid math sort of way. This thing represents a parametric torus, which is NOT the same thing as being able to create a heart shaped Mobius strip, but it is one step closer. Basically, you can give the torus a function which determines the profile of the cross section of the torus as it sweeps around. In this case, I've used the SuperEllipse formula:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superellipse You could just as easily substitute a 2D superformula and make even more wild Torii. The critical piece of code is right here: local seprofiler = param_superellipse.new({ XRadius = 3, ZRadius = 20, N = 0.2, }) local lshape = shape_torus.new({ HoleRadius = offset, ProfileSampler = seprofiler, USteps = 90, WSteps = 180, MinPhi = math.rad(0), MaxPhi = math.rad(360), -- Great circle MinTheta = 0, MaxTheta = math.rad(360), -- profile }) addshape(lshape) Just change the values on that param_superellipse thing and you'll get different shapes. If 'N'=1, for example, you'll get more classic Ellipse/Circle behavior. 'N'<1, you get more squarish. 'N' > 1, up to around 5, and you get the pointy thing going on. While I was out exploring the moon using this model:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14011 I came across a space ship, which you can see modeled here. There was some sort of inscription, which I interpret to mean:
"All Your Toroid Are Belong to Us!" I took a scan of the inside, and as you can see, it's empty in there. Further proof that the aliens have long since left our civilization behind. And also further proof that the moon, and everything that surrounds it, is nothing more than an inflated toy.

Basically a little ball inside of a wiffle ball.  
This really shows off your printer's ability to create something in a single print that otherwise simply couldn't be made!

This is basically a 3d printer's worst nightmare...  
That said, my Solidoodle 3 handled it surprisingly well after only one misprint due to the part coming off the bed.  
I got the part to stick to the bed by applying a TINY dab of superglue on my print bed which the extruder nozzle ran through on the first layer causing the piece to REALLY stick down.  For all the overhangs and bridges, I held a small fan onto the part to rapidly cool the bridged plastic.  Good luck!

description.text:
This is a clip to assist programming circuit boards by mating the ICSP pads to a programmer. I mainly use this for flashing my ESCs with blheli, but many uses for it in the electronics world.

Requires:

  • grippy material to hold the ESC in place ( I use velcro, but you can use weather stripping or anything)
  • rubber band
  • CA glue
  • spring probes. Can be bought anywhere. Here's a link to amazon http://www.amazon.com/0-87mm-Round-Spring-Loaded-Probes/dp/B007Q8487A/

Just solder wires to the pins and glue it to the clip. I've included different clip designs, one with slots for the spring probes, but left some for the user to customize in case they have different spacing pads on their ESC.

I am still trying to understand the Black Art of 3D printing. One thing that I have noticed is the build cabinet temperature makes a huge difference to the flatness of a PLA print. So I have been keeping it at 28-35C and getting great results. Looking for something to make I decided to modify the rear name plate on the build platform to incorporate a digital thermometer. The unit I am using can be found on EBay for A$4-5 and is sold as a fish tank thermometer. Hope someone else finds it useful.
I found that the original design could get in the way of the gantry when you were leveling the build plate. I have reworked the whole back plate to help this problem. Tilting the LCD backwards also make it easier to read.
I use sailfish on my Makerbot so the bed leveling script is different (you move the head by hand) to the standard Makerbot script that moves the print head to preset positions. I believe that this may still cause some issues, please test your setup with this in mind. Normal print operations will not be affected by this back plate.

Not rocket science.  Print, test fit the unit and replace the old back plate with your new bit of bling.  If you are feeling brave you can open the unit before installation and shorten the probe lead to about 100 mm also a small amount  of silicone will hold the probe in place if you find it too lose. Try not to glue the unit in place as you will have to remove it to change battery at some stage. description.text:
Hey all

I designed a 200mm backwards curved impeller because I couldn't find one on here anywhere!

VIDEO OF MY PROTOTYPE PRINT RUNNING
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KhTisIjnOTw&feature=youtu.be

This design is similar to EBM Papst motorized impeller, however, this one <$5 to print, vs $200+ for that one!

This type of fan is also known as Plug Fan. Only an inlet ring is required; NO scroll case is required to get good airflow. The chamber the fan is inside will be pressurized, and it will intake from the middle. You don't need a proper inlet ring for this one, just use a flat sheet of something with a hole under 4cm away from the front of the fan's top ring. I tested it inside a cardboard box. Direction of rotation is CCW facing the front inlet. This is to allow it to be powered with DC brushless fan motor (you will burn it out if load is too high though)

I am using a printer's carriage DC motor to drive it. Using around 15V DC, it rotates at a pretty slow speed, but moves a TON of air for the noise it produces. Increasing the DC voltage to 28V allows it to rotate much faster, and suck a large volume of air through quietly. However, this may burn out the motor if run like this for a long time.

I provided the mount to let you attach it to the motor shaft. You have to drill the hole yourself. If you want to have a different middle part design please let me know and I will upload the autocad file for you to edit? I used some small screws to screw it in.

BALANCING IS VERY IMPORTANT; if someone comes up with a good way, please do share. I did it with trial and error with tape and made it permanent by measuring the same weight of epoxy resin.

Glue the inlet ring firmly to the bottom using epoxy. If you don't, the vanes will shake and make noise.

Please be careful with this fan. Even though it does not require a casing, installation within an enclosed situation is highly encouraged for safety reasons. The rotational inertia and sharp blade edges are dangerous when it is running, and it is advised to not run the fan too fast and inspect rotor for damage before starting . description.text:
This is a mount to fit the smaller version of the excellent Flex3Drive extruder (http://mutley3d.com/Flex3Drive-1/) to a Smartrapcore printer (alu and wood versions). Get a direct drive extruder but add only 85g to your print head. Please be aware the flex3drive is a part you have to buy separately.

This was made by modifying the base of the kossel mini version of flex3drive which now forms the base of the extruder. I am afraid its a bit quick and dirty but it does work. If anyone feels like taking on tidying it up and making it a bit neater and less mashed up then I'd be massively grateful for the help.

I haven't included the clip that holds the hot end as it's the same as the original smart rap core part so just use your old one.

Notes:

Just print it as strong and accurately as possible.
The mount to the print head will print with a little support the flex3drive extruder base needs no support.

Some screw holes might need drilling. a little removal of plastic around the nut traps on the underneath.

Use 2x m3x20 mm bolts to hold the extruder base to the hot end bracket. They should self tap. If using 1.75mm a short piece of bowden tube between the two parts helps guide the filament, make sure this guide goes up into the flex3drive and stops just short of the drive pulley. With 3mm it should be stiff enough for a filament guide not to be needed.

I weighed my kossel Xl effector which now has my flex3drive on it and its 250g total for the whole effector, and that's aluminium and has magballs on it too. Just a titan aero and a pancake stepper weigh 250g without a carriage or anything else attached.

description.text:
We made some experiments with our lasercutting machine and designed a box for the RAMPS electronics including our breakout board for ATX power supplies.
The intention was to make it easy to assemble without needing too much screws or even glue. The result was a push-together system with slide-in connectors. Apart from this single screw you don't need anything else to secure the complete box. Of course the RAMPS and the breakout board as well as the fan have to be screwed on. The box is designed to be mounted to the frame of the BetaPrusa 3D printer or other prusa and mendel variants.
At the front only the USB connector of the RAMPS board is visible.
The holes at the side of the box are for the wiring of the 3D printer and the connection to the ATX power supply. This way, the RAMPS board is boxed in save so no one can touch it when it is operating. It's well ventilated with the fan and in addition it looks cool. The 2PrintBeta team
Simply slide together all parts - almost like a 3D puzzle - and secure the last part with one single screw to prevent it from falling off.

Thought I would share with you all how I machined the extruder bolt for the Itty Bitty Belted Extruder http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:389105.
I realize that not everyone will have the equipment needed but I thought it would be of interest.

This extruder bolt is for 1.75mm filament.

On a lathe centre drill a M8 bolt. Using a milling machine mount the bolt in a dividing head using the the steady. Centre a 4mm slot drill along the axis of the bolt and position the tool along the axis of the bolt to suit.Touch the slot drill on the top of the bolt and zero the Z axis. Move the tool away and drop the Z axis down 1.5mm. Machine the first cut by feeding the Y axis until the centre of the tool is 4.4mm away from the centre of the bolt. Repeat this operation 24 times using the quick indexer on the back of the dividing head.This will create 24 equally spaced notches in the bolt.

I hope that all made sense as it is easier for me to make one than to describe the process.

title: Bowden extruder flex for Lewihe Play & others. (AKA PakoBowden)

description.text:
SPANISH: (See below for english)

Esta es mi idea para un extrusor bowden de 1.75mm para la pequeña impresora coreXY Lewihe Play. Estaba buscando un extrusor bowden que se las pudiera apañar con filamento flexible, así que diseñé esto para hacer unas pruebas. Deja sitio para insertar un tubo de teflón de 4mm(2mm interiores) que se puede fijar en su sitio firmemente con unas tuercas M4 incrustadas. Para colocar los tubos de teflón de 4 y 6mm se usan un par de racores neumáticos. Un rodamiento 624ZZ y un tornillo M4 en el idler, un engrane MK8 (o de 11mm en la V4) en el motor NEMA17, unos tornillos M3, tuercas y un par de muelles son las vitaminas que he usado para construirlo. El diseño deslizante del idler lo mantiene simple y robusto, y la pinza entre el idler y el cuerpo del extrusor te permite eventualmente liberar el filamento de la presión del engranaje para manipularlo simplemente apretando con los dedos, sin siquiera aflojar ni mover ningun tornillo. Como el tubo de teflón del extrusor está fijado con dos tuercas M4 embutidas, no es posible que el tubo se mueva arriba o abajo dentro del extrusor, evitando así cualquier posibilidad de que se atasque o se salga (que me ha pasado con otros extrusores). Una vez colocado y cortado el tubo, la pequeña tolerancia entre el rodamiento 624ZZ y el engrane MK8 no dejan casi sitio para que el filamento se atasque. Cambie la escala Z del espaciador a su medida para permitir que el motor encaje. Decidí poner tubo fijo de teflon tanto en la entrada como en la salida del filamento porque consideré que en la retracción el filamento también debe guiarse con precisión para evitar atascos. No entiendo porque otras soluciones para filamento flexible no incorporan este sistema. He usado un engrane MK8 para mejorar el par de empuje.
Para imprimir: Tanto el idler como el extrusor requieren soporte. Recomiendo imprimir en ABS, con un relleno de un 50% y 3.2mm de borde. Recuerda que deben ser piezas fuertes. Para introducir el tubo de teflón tanto por arriba como por abajo mete la tuerca M4 primero y luego usa el extrusor como grip para la tuerca. Una vez dentro del extrusor corta lo que sobre arriba metiendo un cutter por la ranura encima de la tuerca. Algunas fotos son de un modelo anterior pero equivalente. Si tienes un motor con doble eje puedes usar la rueda incluida o usar esta: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1542763

Tambien recomendado: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1549887

Queda por hacer: Nada. Todo funciona correctamente. Proyecto concluido. Si os haceis uno poned un MAKE!! me encantaría verlo!!!

UPDATE (30-MAY-2016): Fotos de un V4 recién hecho.

UPDATE (26-MAY-2016): Nuevo modelo V4 para una polea de 11mm. Similar a la V3 pero rediseñado y con algún añadido como el colector de residuos y mejores tolerancias. Lo siento por el cambio de diseño pero tenía que hacer otro extrusor y solo me quedaban poleas de 11mm en la bolsa... Incluso cuando la polea MK8 tiene más par, estas poleas de 11mm tienen mejor agarre del filamento debido a su diseño con los dientes más profundos, y esto no es malo para un sistema bowden donde hay mayor presión en el filamento que en los extrusores directos. También he añadido unos insertos para los agujeros de los tornillos y tuercas que a modo de embellecedores podeis imprimir en PLA y darle un toque de color... Tambien puedes bajarte la versión sin logo e imprimirselo en colores y luego pegarlo, o ponerle el tuyo propio si quieres.

UPDATE (10-MAY-2016):Pequeños cambios en el idler para requerir menos ajustes.

UPDATE (25-APR-2016): He eliminado las fotos de prototipos anteriores para no confundir.

UPDATE (30-MAR-2016): Fotos de un V3 recien hecho.

UPDATE (29-MAR-2016):Nueva versión V3. He colocado mejor los huecos para cortar el tubo de teflón y eso me ha obligado a añadir unos refuerzos para las roscas de los adaptadores de tubo. He añadido un sistema de bloqueo del idler con un tornillo M3 y un muelle. Versiones anteriores eliminadas. Añadido logotipo 3D, Z-escalalo a tu gusto.

UPDATE (26-MAR-2016): He añadido fotos. Al final he tenido tiempo. .STL de la rueda manual. añadido Sorprendentemente ha funcionado con filaflex y ninjaflex!!! No me lo puedo creer!!!

UPDATE (26-MAR-2016): Cambiado el diseño del separador 'strong' para que las tolerancias del idler no puedan dar problemas en el encaje del bloque.

UPDATE (22-MAR-2016): Para poder usar tornillos M3 para el NEMA17 más cortos he tenido que reajustar tanto el cuerpo del extrusor como el Idler. Estas dos piezas van juntas y solo son compatibles con los separadores. Para distinguirlas las he llamado V2. He aprovechado para dejarlas un poco más chulas. Si vas a usar la V2, úsala con el idler strong V2 y un separador. No he rediseñado el idler normal para la V2.

UPDATE (21-MAR-2016): Recalculados STL's, use el slicer que quiera para generar soportes. Fuente FreeCAD publicado. Recomiendo no usar un adaptador de tubo en la salida del extrusor para que toda la conducción del filamento hasta el hotend vaya guiada por tubo. Por eso he suprimido la rosca para el adaptador de salida. Cambiado el diseño del espaciador para la versión 'strong' para permitir que se pueda extraer completamente el idler sin aflojar el extrusor.

UPDATE (17-MAR-2016): Los .STLs de la version 'strong' se han cambiado para incluir soporte y una base anti-warp (o con soporte y pared térmica para el idler). Ahora se imprimirán mas fácilmente. Desactiva el soporte en tu slicer ya que les he añadido un soporte a medida. Solo tendrás que quitarlo y limar un poco una vez impreso. Perdón, aún estoy preparando los archivos FreeCAD para publicarlos.

UPDATE (15-MAR-2016): Vale, vale. para todos aquellos que teneis problemas para introducir el tubo de teflón os he hecho unas ranuras para que podais usar un cutter para cortar el tubo por encima de la tuerca.

ENGLISH:
This is my idea for a bowden 1.75mm extruder for the tiny Lewihe Play corexy printer. I was looking for a bowden extruder that could feed flexible filament, so I designed this to make a proof. It provides room to insert a 4mm(inner 2mm) PTFE tube that can be fixed firmly in place with an embedded M4 nut. A pair of neumatic adapters are used to attach the 6mm and the 4mm PTFE tubes. A 624ZZ bearing and a M4 screw used in the idler, an MK8 gear (or an 11mm in V4) on the NEMA17 motor, some M3 screws, nuts and a couple springs are the vitamins used to build it up. The sliding design of the idler keeps it simple and strong, and the clamp between the body and the idler allows you to eventually free the filament from the gear by just pressing your fingers on it, without loosening any idler screw. As the inner 4mm PTFE tube on the extruder is fixed with a pair of M4 nuts embedded in the extruder's body, there is no chance for it to move up or down into the extruder, eliminating absolutely the possibility of jamming by the tube (that happened to me with other extruders). Once the tube is fixed and cut in place, the little tolerance from the 624ZZ bearing and the MK8 gear allows almost no room for filament jamming. Z-scale the spacer to your needs to allow room to the motor's latch. I choose to put PTFE tube both in the in/out of the filament 'cause I consider that filament should also be precisely guided to avoid jams even on retraction moves. I don't understand why other flex solutions doesn't include this. I have used a small MK8 gear to increase torque. If you have a two-axis motor you can use the included wheel o use this: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1542763

Also recommended: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1549887

Printing instructions: Both idler and extruder body require complete support for ovenhanging parts. Recommended print in ABS. Infill at least 50%. Shell 3.2mm. Remember this have to be strong parts. Pics are from a previous model but similar performance.

TODO: Nothing. It works fine for me. I conclude this project. If you make one, put it in a MAKE!! I'll love to see it!!

UPDATE (30-MAY-2016): Pics of a just made V4.

UPDATE (26-MAY-2016): NEW V4 model for a 11mm pulley. Similar to V3 but redesigned and with some bonus like the debris collector and enhanced tolerances for printing. Sorry, I needed to make one extruder more and there was only 11mm pulleys left in the bag... Even when a smaller gear like the MK8 has more torque, due to the deeper teeth of this 11mm gear, it has a better grip for the filament and that is not bad for a bowden solution where pressures are higher than on direct driven extruders. I also added some insets for the nuts/bolts holes you can print on PLA to give it a touch of color... You can also download the nologo version and print the logo in colors and stick it, or even put there your own. It's up to you!

UPDATE (10-MAY-2016):Minor changes in the idler to ease setup.

UPDATE (25-APR-2016): Removed pics from old prototypes to avoid confusing.

UPDATE (30-MAR-2016): Newly made V3 pics added.

UPDATE (29-MAR-2016):New version V3. Relocated holes for cutting PTFE tube, that has forced me to add some reinforcement for the tube adapters threads. Added a idler blocking system with a M3 bolt/spring/nut. Older versions deleted. 3D logo added, Z-scale it as you want.

UPDATE (26-MAR-2016): Pics added. Finally I got time. Manual wheel .STL for double axis motor added. Surprinsingly it worked with filaflex and ninjaflex!! I can't believe it!!

UPDATE (26-MAR-2016): Strong idler separator desing changed. This way idler's tolerances can't be a problem in the block fit.

UPDATE (22-MAR-2016): To be able to use shorter M3 screws to fix te extruder's body I had to readjust the extruder and the idler. This two new parts come together and are only compatible with the separators. I have called them V2 to distinguish between them. I've had the chance to improve the design to make it a little bit cool. If you are going to use the V2, use it with the V2 strong idler and a separator. I haven't redesigned the normal idler for the V2.

UPDATE (21-MAR-2016): New STL's, use your preferred slicer to generate sopport. FreeCAD source published. I don't recommend usign a tube adapter on the extruder's output, to allow the filament to be totally guided through PTFE to the hotend. That's the reason for trimming the adapter's thread. Changed design of the strong spacer to allow the idler to be removed without detaching the extruder.

UPDATE (17-MAR-2016): .STLs of the strong version have been changed to include support and anti-warp base (or with support and thermal wall for the idler). There should be easier to print now. Turn off support on your slicer as an specific support has been added. Just take it off and file a bit once printed. Sorry, I am still preparing Freecad sources to be published.

UPDATE (15-MAR-2016): Ok, Ok. For those of you having problems installing the PTFE tube I have made for you a version of the extruder with some grooves for using a cutter to cut off the tube above the M4 nut.

title: Toad 110 - Micro FPV Quad - (8.5mm Hubsan X4 Motors)

description.text:
This is a requested re-work of my Frog 100 frame. I've tweaked the size a little to allow bigger FC's such as naze32/afro32/cc3d to fit inside. I believe it would also fit beefs brushed FC, but I haven't got one to try.

**Added Updated Revision 3 Files. Tweaked some of the frame holes to strengthen some weak areas I found through aggressive testing :)

I've made a few of these for friends who want to learn about flying quads, cheap and fun. :)

When using a cleanflight based FC, I use my custom 6.2 Amp Brushed ESC's

Parts list:
Flight Controller + ESC or RTF Flight Controller
4 x 8.5mm Motors (Hubsan H107C A23)
200-500 Mah Lipo
M3 Hex Spacer 10-15mm *8

Optional Camera - either fpv or video
The camera on the image is a hubsan 2mp video camera cheapo clone. It's slung underneath and running off the same lipo as the motors + fc.
I also have a little stand alone Boscam CM205 with a 100mah I stick on top if i want FPV.

I have used a stripped down Flysky RX soldered to the naze32 with my custom ESC. This is glued to under the top plate. I also replaced the stock antenna with a little wire antenna (range is still good enough for me).

You could also use a standard quadcopter FC with cleanflight/betaflight with the ESC output in brushed motor mode and some of my custom 6.2 Amp Brushed ESC's

If running without FPV then 500mah are fine, I find it a bit weak if its fully loaded and switched to 260/300mah lipos.

Prusa I3

No

No

Notes:

I usually print in PLA, and only in very heavy crashes do things break. Most crashes its all fine. I would adjust the fill/resolution to get better layer bonding. I've printed this on my prusa I3 at 80mm/sec speed and its been structurally ok.

title: Little Nema14 Belted Flex Extruder for E3DV6

description.text:
This is a design I am working on. The only files available at this moment are the FreeCAD sources. This is a extruder for a E3DV6 1.75mm and a NEMA14 motor working with a GT2 belt and metalic (normal aluminum gears from CNC projects) using a typical M8 hobbed bolt to be installed on a I3 style printer. I am working on a bowden version and NEMA17/23 versions. Also an adapter for different type of hotends to make the thing modular is being developed.
this project was initially expected to be finished anytime between APR-MAY 2016, (but due to a tight schedule I have not enough time to finish it at that date. It will take some months till I can continue this project, but don't make mistake, it's not dead! Even a prototype is working at date! But still not ready for production). This will work specialy fine with flexible filaments 'cause it reduces to the minimum the distance between the hotend/hobbed bolt and the filament is entirely guided through a 4mm PTFE tube. It is small, light and simple. The NEMA14 motor can be moved up/down to accomodate the GT2 belts of your choice and uses typical bearings/screws/nuts we all have around. It is intended to be installed on any standard I3 carriage, but it is easy to change to your own 'cause you get the sources.

Changes/updates will be posted here when available.

remixed_from.title: Logitech C270/310 Universal Webcam Mount (Scews or 3M VHB)

description.text:
This is a mount for the Logitech c270 webcam. It can be used on just about anything.

I needed it to mount to a 20x40mm extrusion rail on my 3D printer. It fastens in place with a 3D printed bolt and can easily be taken off and moved around. I really didn't want to drill holes anywhere to install a camera so this one just screws down wherever you need it.

The mount is very solid and does not vibrate. Great for mounting as a 3D printer camera, webcam, or security camera.

Printer:

C-bot coreXY

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

200 micron

Infill:

35%

Notes:

Everything was placed in this plate to print as is. You do not need to move any of the files around or reorient them.

You may need to print the files individually if you have a poorly tuned printer. Some of the parts in the plate are really close together and if your printer is not set up right it may have trouble making all the pieces.

Also, if your printer is not well tuned you may have trouble printing the bolt and clamp due to the threads. The bolt used in this model is the exact same as the Makerbolt, so if you can print the Makerbolt without a problem you will be fine.
You will need four M5 bolts and M5 nuts to connect the camera arms together. After that you can move them however you like ant tighten them down.

For this design I merged the camera mount for the c270 webcam from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1159406 with the bolt clamp from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1159406.

I made a minor adjustment to the clamp to make it larger so it would fit on a 20mm extrusion rail. I also made one of the camera arms a little thinner.

I tried a couple of drum models but didn't feel they were very accurate so I designed my own. This is modeled after a 55 gallon drum I made my UDS (Ugly Drum Smoker) out of but with the strengthening ribs slightly more pronounced for visual effect.

I added a 'hollow' version which prints much nicer than just the original with no top layers. I print it with enough bottom layers to make the bottom solid and 2 horizontal perimeters.

15% infill works well if you're making it enclosed, otherwise 3 perimeters is sufficient for open top. .1mm looks great but .2mm looks good as well. Rotate it 90 degrees in your slicer to print upright.

This was my first 'from scratch' 3D model (Fusion 360) and I'm quite pleased with it.
